## Fixing failing tests

Always generate hypotheses first without writing code, then come up with a plan. Follow the following rules when fixing failing tests:

1. Understand the test first - Carefully analyze what the test is checking for before making any changes.  
2. Preserve the test's intent - Fix implementations to make tests pass, not the other way around (unless the test itself is flawed).  
3. Diagnose before modifying - Explain the root cause of failure before making changes.  
4. Make minimal changes - Implement the smallest possible fix that addresses the issue.  
5. Maintain compatibility - Ensure fixes don't break other tests or functionality.  
6. Explain your reasoning - Document why a particular solution was chosen.  
7. Verify the fix - Show that the test passes after your changes.  
8. Identify related issues - Flag similar issues that might exist elsewhere in the codebase.  
9. Consider edge cases - Ensure your solution handles boundary conditions the test might be targeting.  
10. Respect existing patterns - Follow the codebase's established conventions and architecture.

## Debugging issues

When debugging make sure to put console.log's in place so the user can clearly follow what's going one and what is the though process behind the implemented fixes.
Make sure to try and use the outputs of the console logs to debug issues instead of trying to guess where the problem is.

